  "prompt": "Why do almost all living things depend on green plants for food?",
  "response": "Almost all living things depend on green plants for food because green plants are primary producers that form the base of most food chains and food webs. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Photosynthesis\n- Green plants are the only organisms that can convert solar energy into chemical energy through photosynthesis\n- They use sunlight, carbon dioxide, and water to produce glucose (food) and oxygen\n- This process creates organic compounds that serve as energy sources for other organisms\n\n2. Energy Transfer\n- Plants convert inorganic compounds into organic materials that can be used by other organisms\n- Herbivores eat plants directly\n- Carnivores eat herbivores, and higher-level predators eat other animals\n- This creates a food chain where energy is transferred from plants to other organisms\n\n3. Ecosystem Foundation\n- Plants are the primary producers in most ecosystems\n- They support the entire food web by providing:\n   - Direct food source for herbivores\n   - Oxygen production\n   - Habitat and shelter for other organisms\n\n4. Nutritional Value\n- Plants contain essential nutrients, carbohydrates, proteins, and other compounds necessary for life\n- They are the original source of energy and nutrients for most living systems\n\nThis fundamental role makes green plants critical for sustaining life on Earth.",
